{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a478352b-b634-4e66-aa54-ac585f907adb","content":"In .NET MAUI, those `Application`-level overrides are gone. The equivalent is on the **`Window`** class. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` and use a custom `Window` subclass (or subscribe to events):\n\n**Mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | .NET MAUI (`Window`) |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `OnCreated()` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `OnStopped()` |\n| `OnResume()` | `OnResumed()` |\n\n**Example:**\n\n```csharp\n// App.xaml.cs\npublic partial class App : Application\n{\n    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n    {\n        return new MyWindow(new AppShell());\n    }\n}\n\n// MyWindow.cs\npublic class MyWindow : Window\n{\n    public MyWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }\n\n    protected override void OnCreated()    // was OnStart\n    {\n        base.OnCreated();\n        // initialization logic\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnStopped()    // was OnSleep\n    {\n        base.OnStopped();\n        // save state, pause work\n    }\n\n    protected override void OnResumed()    // was OnResume\n    {\n        base.OnResumed();\n        // refresh data, reconnect\n    }\n}\n```\n\nYou also get `OnActivated()`, `OnDeactivated()`, and `OnDestroying()` for finer-grained control. For **platform-specific** lifecycle hooks, use `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f50192b3-ee26-4f4d-8db7-b28e10098fb9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or the `ILifecycleBuilder` in `MauiProgram.cs`. Specifically:\n\n- The `Application` class still exists but the recommended approach is to use **Window lifecycle events** by overriding `CreateWindow()` and subscribing to events, or by subclassing `Window`.\n\n\n- You can also configure platform-specific lifecycle events through `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` in `MauiProgram.cs`, which gives you finer control over events like `Created`, `Activated`, `Deactivated`, `Stopped`, `Resumed`, and `Destroying`.\n\nLet me give a clear, practical answer now.","outputTokens":886,"requestId":"9BC4:11AB75:621ABA6:6D4D17A:69EC0F2C"},"id":"3dfb27c4-116c-4059-8692-ec0504b818fb","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:47:56.565Z","parentId":"ce42ba9c-a7ba-4c64-9930-95b9c2ca5a9d"}
